title: New Florida Bill Could Let Homeowners Vote to Dissolve Their HOA — What It Means for 2026
author: Steve Feler
excerpt: Florida homeowners may soon have the power to dissolve their HOAs under House Bill 657. The bill proposes a clear process for ending associations, increases accountability, and could reshape community governance in 2026. Learn what this means for buyers, sellers, and Florida neighborhoods.
content:
Florida homeowners may soon have a new way to take control of their communities. House Bill 657, known as the Homeowners’ Association Dissolution and Accountability Act, proposes a legal process allowing residents to dissolve their HOA if enough homeowners agree.

The bill reflects growing frustration among some homeowners who feel constrained by high fees, strict rules, and limited transparency. If passed, it could be one of the most significant changes to HOA legislation in decades. Here’s a breakdown of what you need to know.

How the HOA Dissolution Process Would Work

HB 657 outlines a clear, multi-step process for dissolving an HOA:

1. Petition Threshold: 20% of Homeowners

The process begins with a petition signed by at least 20% of all property owners in the community. This triggers the official dissolution procedure.

2. Mandatory Board Meeting

Once the petition meets the threshold, the HOA board must hold a meeting within 60 days to discuss the petition and prepare for a vote.

3. Vote to Dissolve

During the meeting, all homeowners vote on the proposal. Dissolution requires approval from two-thirds (⅔) of all voting members.

4. If the Vote Fails

If the community votes against dissolution, homeowners must wait 18 months before attempting another petition.

5. After Approval

If the vote passes, a trustee oversees the termination process, which includes:

  • Settling debts and contracts
  • Selling or transferring common assets
  • Distributing remaining funds to homeowners according to the plan

These procedures mirror those already in place for condominium associations in Florida.

Additional Reforms in HB 657

Beyond creating a path to dissolve HOAs, the bill includes measures to improve accountability and transparency:

  • Community Association Court Program: Establishes specialized courts to handle HOA disputes more efficiently.
  • Governing Document Updates: New associations (after July 1, 2026) must include “Kaufman language” that automatically incorporates future statutory changes. Existing associations can vote to adopt this language.
  • Removing Presuit Mediation: Eliminates mandatory mediation before filing disputes, streamlining conflict resolution.
  • Penalties for Non-Compliance: Officers or directors who fail to follow procedural requirements could face fines up to $5,000 per violation and removal from their positions.

Supporters vs. Opponents

Supporters Say:

  • It empowers homeowners to hold boards accountable.
  • Communities could escape dysfunctional or unresponsive associations.
  • Increased transparency and homeowner rights are overdue reforms.

Opponents Warn:

  • HOAs manage essential services like roads, landscaping, and amenities that protect property values.
  • Allowing 20% of homeowners to trigger a vote could destabilize well-run associations.
  • There are practical concerns about asset ownership and infrastructure post-dissolution.

Where HB 657 Stands

As of mid-December 2025, HB 657 has been filed and awaits committee referral in the Florida House. No companion Senate bill exists yet. If passed and signed by the Governor, the bill could take effect as early as July 1, 2026.

What This Means for Buyers and Sellers

For Buyers:

  • Greater control over HOA governance may make HOA communities more appealing.
  • Uncertainty about future changes could be a double-edged sword.

For Sellers:

  • Dissolution could impact property values or saleability if a community ends its HOA mid-market.
  • Clear rules and transparency may boost buyer confidence.

Final Takeaway

House Bill 657 represents one of the most ambitious HOA reform efforts in Florida’s history. It offers a potential exit strategy for homeowners unhappy with their associations while sparking a broader conversation about HOA power, homeowner rights, and community governance. Whether it becomes law—and how it will be used—remains to be seen, but its implications could reshape Florida communities in 2026 and beyond.

title: Latest Status Update: Property Tax Relief and Potential Removal for Homestead Properties in Florida
author: Steve Feler
excerpt:
As of December 19, 2025, property taxes have not been eliminated for homestead properties in Florida. Homeowners continue to receive the standard homestead exemption (now approximately $50,722 after inflation adjustment) and the Save Our Homes 3% assessment cap.

Governor Ron DeSantis is pushing for major relief, including a proposed $1,000 rebate in 2025 and long-term elimination of non-school homestead taxes via constitutional amendments potentially on the 2026 ballot. No full removal is in effect yet—significant changes would likely start in 2027 or later if voters approve them.
content:
Florida homeowners with homestead exemptions continue to benefit from existing property tax protections, but there is no full removal or elimination of property taxes on homestead properties at this time. However, significant proposals are advancing that could lead to major reductions or partial elimination, potentially appearing on the 2026 ballot. Governor Ron DeSantis has made property tax relief a priority, pushing for long-term changes while proposing short-term rebates.

Current Homestead Property Tax Exemptions

Florida's homestead exemption remains one of the strongest in the nation, reducing the taxable value of primary residences:

  • Standard Exemption: Up to $50,000 total.
  • First $25,000 applies to all taxing authorities (including schools).
  • Additional $25,000 applies to non-school taxes (counties, cities, special districts) for properties assessed above $50,000.
  • 2025 Inflation Adjustment: Thanks to Amendment 5, approved by voters in November 2024, the second $25,000 exemption is now adjusted annually for inflation based on the Consumer Price Index (CPI). For the 2025 tax year, this increases the total exemption to approximately $50,722 for qualifying properties. This provides modest additional relief without affecting school taxes.
  • Save Our Homes Cap: Annual assessed value increases are limited to 3% (or CPI, whichever is lower) for homesteaded properties.

These benefits apply only to primary residences where owners have filed for and received the homestead exemption.

Proposed Short-Term Relief: $1,000 Rebate

In 2025, Governor DeSantis proposed an average $1,000 property tax rebate for over 5.1 million homesteaded properties. This would target state-mandated school taxes, with rebates potentially issued in December 2025. The plan aims to provide immediate relief while maintaining full funding for schools. As of now, this remains a proposal pending legislative action.

Push for Long-Term Elimination

Governor DeSantis has advocated for completely eliminating property taxes on homesteaded primary residences, calling them "rent to the government." His ultimate goal requires a constitutional amendment, which needs voter approval in 2026.

  • Florida House Proposals: In October 2025, the House released multiple constitutional amendment proposals for the 2026 ballot, including:
  • HJR 201: Straight elimination of all non-school homestead property taxes (counties, cities, etc.), while preserving school levies and prohibiting cuts to law enforcement funding.
  • HJR 203: Phased elimination of non-school homestead taxes over 10 years.
  • HJR 205: Full elimination for seniors (65+).
  • Other options include larger exemptions (e.g., $100,000 additional for insured properties via HJR 209) and enhanced portability of benefits.

Several of these (including HJR 201, 205, 209, and 211) advanced through committees in late 2025 and are positioned for further consideration in the 2026 legislative session (January-March 2026).

  • Challenges and Concerns: Local governments warn that eliminating homestead taxes could cost billions in revenue (estimates range from $14-18 billion annually), leading to service cuts in rural areas, higher fees, or tax shifts to businesses, renters, and non-homestead properties. Studies highlight potential strain on police, fire, and infrastructure funding.

title: Selling a Home With Solar Panels in Florida? Read This First
author: Steve Feler, Tampa Bay Real Estate Consultant
excerpt: Selling a Florida home with solar panels? Solar can be a big plus for buyers — but only if the details are clear. This quick guide walks homeowners through what buyers ask, what documents to have ready, and how to make solar a selling advantage.
content:
Selling a Florida Home With Solar Panels? Here’s What to Know

Solar panels are a big plus for many Florida buyers — lower electric bills and lots of sunshine make them appealing. Still, selling a home with solar does come with a few extra details to sort out.

The biggest things buyers usually ask about:

  • Are the panels owned, financed, or leased?
  • Can they see electric bill savings?
  • Is the paperwork easy to understand?

Having your solar documents ready and being clear upfront can make a big difference. When buyers understand the benefits, solar often becomes a selling point instead of a question mark.

If you’re thinking about selling — or just planning ahead — a quick conversation can help you avoid surprises and keep things smooth.

No pressure, just helpful guidance.
